In TypeScript, when one wishes to inform the type system that a variable which theoretically could be of multiple types will, in practice, be of a singular, specific type, one may employ a type assertion. Type assertions are akin to type casts in other languages, but they perform no special checking or restructuring of data. They operate purely at the level of the TypeScript type system, serving as a means to signal to the compiler one's confidence in the type of the entity in question.

To utilize a type assertion, one may employ the `as` keyword, followed by the desired type. Here is an exemplar of such usage:

```typescript
let someValue: any = "This is a string";

// Asserting that someValue is indeed a string
let strLength: number = (someValue as string).length;
```

Alternatively, one may use the angle-bracket syntax, which is reminiscent of type casting in languages such as C#:

```typescript
let someValue: any = "This is a string";

// Asserting that someValue is indeed a string
let strLength: number = (<string>someValue).length;
```

It is imperative to note that type assertions do not alter the runtime nature of the value; they merely signal to the TypeScript compiler one's certitude regarding the type of the value at hand. Consequently, one must exercise caution and judiciousness when employing type assertions, as misuse can lead to a disjunction between the compile-time assumptions and the actual runtime behavior, potentially resulting in errors that the type system will not detect.

